description:
Agricultural researchers in Ghana have boosted numbers of native shea trees.
Shea nuts are widely used in food and cosmetics globally.
Ghana is already a leading exporter of shea products.
New grafting techniques allow trees to bear fruit in 3–5 years instead of 15.
The industry supports over one million people across the country.
Ghana aims to increase exports from 100,000 to 400,000 tonnes annually.
Researchers hope this breakthrough will strengthen livelihoods and meet rising global demand.

Al Jazeera’s Ama Boateng.

description:
Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan has condemned Israel’s recognition of Somaliland as illegitimate and destabilising.
Speaking alongside Somalia’s President Hassan Sheikh Mahmud in Istanbul, Erdogan reaffirmed Turkiye’s support for Somalia’s unity and territorial integrity.
Somalia’s president said the move was a violation of his country’s sovereignty and warned it could fuel divisions and embolden armed groups.
Erdogan accused Israel of breaching international law and undermining stability in the Horn of Africa.
The talks highlighted Turkiye’s long-term security, economic and diplomatic partnership with Somalia.
Protests also erupted in Mogadishu, with demonstrators rejecting Israel’s move as foreign interference.

Al Jazeera's Sinem Koseoglu reports from Istanbul.
Abdinor Dahir, an independent researcher and political analyst on Turkiye–Africa relations, said the decision threatens Somalia’s stability. He warned it also endangers Turkiye’s strategic, economic and security inter
title: Turkiye and Somalia denounce Israel’s recognition of breakaway Somaliland

Beijing named the drills Justice Mission 2025 and they are widely seen as a show of force as China seeks to assert its claim that Taiwan is part of its sovereign territory.
The drills come on the heels of an $11 billion arms deal between the United States and Taiwan.
And although the US was not mentioned, Beijing called the drills a 'stern warning' to 'external forces'.
So will these tensions be contained?

description:
Khaleda ⁠Zia, Bangladesh’s first female prime minister and a towering figure in the country’s turbulent politics, has died at the age of 79 after a prolonged illness, according to her party.
In a statement on Tuesday, the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) said Khaleda died at 6am local time (00:00 GMT).
Our beloved national leader is no longer with us,” the BNP said.
“We pray for the forgiveness of her soul and request everyone to offer prayers for her departed soul,” it said.
Bangladesh has declared three days of state mourning. Asif Nazrul, who holds the law portfolio in the interim government, said Khaleda’s funeral will be held on Wednesday, with funeral prayers to be held in front of parliament after midday prayers, before she is buried alongside her late husband, the assassinated former President Ziaur Rahman.

The head of Yemen's presidential council, supported by Saudi Arabia, says Emirati backed forces in the country should leave within 24 hours.
That follows a Saudi air strike on the port of Mukalla in Yemen, carried out after two ships arrived carrying weapons destined for southern separatist forces.
Mukalla is in Yemen's Hadramout province, that was recently seized by the separatist Southern Transitional Council. 
Saudi state media say the ships came from the port of Fujairah in the UAE.  
Saudi officials say they arrived late last week without official permits and had disabled their tracking systems.
The air strike did not hit either ship and there were no reports of injuries.

Khaled Batarfi is a political analyst, and he says it's unclear how realistic the 24-hour deadline is for Emirati-backed separatist forces to withdraw from Yemen.

Video shows the aftermath of a Saudi-led attack on Yemen’s Mukalla port, targeting a large quantity of weapons and combat vehicles that were being offloaded from ships arriving from the UAE. Yemen's presidential council has cancelled a defence deal with the UAE and ordered all UAE forces to leave Yemen within 24 hours.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
China is holding a second day of military drills around Taiwan, as tensions between Taipei and Beijing escalate. 
China launched missiles into the Taiwan strait near Pingtan Island, the closest Chinese island to Taiwan. 
That comes alongside Chinese naval drills at sea in areas surrounding Taiwan, demonstrating their ability to blockade the island. 
Meanwhile, Taiwan has responded by scrambling fighter jets from a base at Hsinchu on its western coast.  

Al Jazeera’s Katrina Yu is monitoring the situation from Beijing, China and Zein Basravi is standing by at Hsinchu airbase in Taiwan

A tense stand-off in the Caribbean and the eastern Pacific has ramped up again. 
The US has launched a fresh round of strikes in the region including, it claims, within Venezuela. 
That's as President Nicolas Maduro looks to shore up his country's military capabilities.

Al Jazeera’s Patty Culhane reports from Washington, DC.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The United Nations Security Council has met for an emergency session, after Israel became the first country to recognise Somaliland as an independent and sovereign state. Israel said the recognition is based on extensive dialogue during the past year.  
But most council members condemned the action saying it violates international law and the UN Charter.

Al Jazeera’s Gabriel Elizondo reports from UN headquarters in New York.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
US President Donald Trump is hosting Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in Florida. 
One of the main points of discussion has been the implementation of the Gaza ceasefire plan. 
Netanyahu says it should not move into phase two until the remains of the final deceased Israeli captive are handed over. 
But Trump is eager to keep up momentum. 

Al Jazeera’s Shihab Rattansi reports from Palm Beach in Florida.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Former Bangladeshi Prime Minister Khaleda Zia has died at the age of 80. The wife of an assassinated military leader, Zia was the first elected prime minister after the restoration of democracy in the 1990s. Her bitter rivalry with Sheikh Hasina had defined politics in the country for three decades.   
Her Bangladesh National Party announced Zia passed away early on Tuesday, soon after dawn prayers. 

Al Jazeera’s Charles Stratford looks back on her life.
